SUMMARIZER="D">  

An engine room fire Wednesday disabled a cruise ship off the Mexican
coast, but the crew extinguished the blaze.

The Navy cutter Vigilant escorted the 465-foot ship, the Scandinavian
Star, into port as a precaution, according to Chief Petty Officer Luis
Diaz of the U.S. Coast Guard in Miami.

There were no injuries from the fire, but a 71-year-old St. Petersburg
man suffered a heart attack and was being taken home aboard a Coast
Guard plane.

The Scandinavian Star was on a 3-day cruise to Cozumel, Mexico, and
was returning to St. Petersburg when the fire broke out about 8
a.m. EST Wednesday.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881109-0149" 
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="D">  

The cruise ship Song of America was forced to return to port after an
engine seized up and started a small fire, but no one was hurt.

The ship left Miami on Sunday with about 1,300 passengers on a
Caribbean cruise.  Rick Steck, a spokesman for Royal Caribbean Cruise
Line said the fire was quickly doused by crewmembers.  The passengers,
who had been brought on deck, were allowed to resume the evening's
activities.

The 705-foot ship turned around and returned to Cozumel on its
remaining three engines to replenish firefighting supplies. The
passengers stayed aboard, and the ship will return to Miami on
Thursday or Friday.  </SUM>

