SUMMARIZER="D">
  
Someone sat a fire early today in a storage room on the luxury liner
Regent Star, five days after the ship ran aground in Delaware Bay
after another fire cut off power, authorities said.

No passengers were aboard and no injuries were reported in the blaze
which was controlled in 90 minutes said a fire department dispatcher.

Just Sunday, the 20,000-ton liner was on its way from Jamaica to
Philadelphia when a small fire prompted a power loss, allowing the
ship to drift onto a sandbar.  None of the passengers were injured and
were taken off the ship by ferry on Monday.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881017-0098"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="D">  

Fire broke out aboard a Soviet passenger liner carrying French
tourists on a cruise of the Mediterranean, but the crew put out the
blaze and no passengers were injured, Tass reported Monday.

The ship docked at the Maltese port of Valletta and the tourists were
expected to continue their voyage on another Soviet ship.

This was the second fire aboard a Soviet cruise ship in recent months.
On May 18, a blaze broke out on Priamurye while it was in the Japanese
port of Osaka.  Eleven Soviets were killed in that fire and 26 others
were hospitalized in critical condition, Tass reported.  </SUM>

<SUM
